Scenario

A randomized control trial is being conducted on an intervention designed to reduce girls engagement in risky sexual behavior. The variable condition within the dataset states whether the participant was in the control or intervention condition.

Fit a model evaluating the effect of the intervention, controlling for the age of the participant and their adverse childhood experiences score (aces), on their sexual risk score.

d %>% 
  mutate(condition = factor(condition),
         condition = relevel(condition, ref = "Control"))

In the space below, briefly explain the results of the investigation. Interpret the coefficient for the intervention. Reference the unique variance accounted for by the intervention, as well as the uncertainty of the estimate.

The model suggests that, when controlling for ACEs, girls in the intervention condition had a significantly higher sexual risk scores (\(b = 0.26, SE = 0.12, t = 2.14, p = 0.03\)) than girls in the control condition. Overall, the model accounted for approximately 15% of the total variability in sexual risk scores, while the intervention uniquely accounted for 3.4% of the total variability.

In the space below, describe how your calculation corresponded to the squared semi-partial correlation you calculated previously. Explain why the values are or are not similar.

The difference in the \(R^2\) values is exactly the same because the squared semi-partial correlation represents the unique variance accounted for by the model, which can also be estimated by looking at the differences in the model \(R^2\) between two models with only one variable differing.

Produce a plot to inspect outliers in the code chunk below. Ive provided some sample code can use, or you can use alternative methods if youd prefer.

d <- d %>%
    mutate(cook_d = cooks.distance(m1))

ggplot(d, aes(id, cook_d)) +
        geom_label(aes(label = id))

Produce a plot of the fitted values against the model residuals in the chunk below

ggplot(m1, aes(.fitted, .resid)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Do you notice anything in these plots that appears concerning?

No.Even the largest Cooks D is very small and likely not unduly influential. Although there is possibly a slight relation with the fitted/residual plot, and there is some evidence of heteroskedasticy, the violations are unlikely to have much effect on the overall model results.
